{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476921","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476921"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:53:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:53:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13991"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583821","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583821"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:30:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:30:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13991"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13991","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13991"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.57,0.04,0.05,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6625"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110418"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6625"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13991"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92682"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1120"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6399"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13448"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31250"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41612"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49647"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110418"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 15-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a five-hour history of left scrotal pain and swelling. He reports some nausea with the pain and no vomiting. He was playing football and was hit directly in the groin by the ball six hours ago. He describes that the pain initially went away but then came back severely after the game. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On further questioning, he reports being sexually active with one partner and using condoms inconsistently. He denies dysuria but has had white discharge from the penis. His parent suggests he has a low pain-tolerance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed with vital signs within normal limits. The left hemiscrotum is swollen and tender with some slight bruising seen over the upper pole of testes. The cremasteric reflex is absent on the left side. There is white discharge from the penis with surrounding redness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Doppler ultrasound of the scrotum","Urgent surgical exploration","Oral antibiotics and follow-up in 48 hours","Urinalysis and urine culture","Ice pack application and analgesia"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step in management for this patient is \u003Cstrong\u003Eurgent surgical exploration\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient\u0027s sexual history could be a potential risk for sexually transmitted infections (STIs), and history of recent trauma could suggest acute bruising, however it is not possible to clearly exclude testicular torsion with the history of severe pain, absent cremasteric reflex, swollen testes and presence of nausea. Thus surgical exploration should be completed. Urgent surgical treatment especially within the first six hours of symptom onset is essential to maximise the chances of testicular salvage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003EDoppler ultrasound of the scrotum\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful in diagnosing testicular torsion, it should not delay surgical intervention when the clinical suspicion is high. In this case, with a clear history and examination findings consistent with torsion, proceeding directly to surgery is the most appropriate course of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral antibiotics and follow-up in 48 hours\u003C/strong\u003E would be more appropriate for suspected epididymitis or other STIs. However, the acute onset and severity of symptoms in this case make torsion more likely than infection, though it may be likely that he has a chlamydia infection as well.  The most urgent next step in management is surgical exploration.  It is important to remember that there may be two or three pathologies occurring at the same time rather than all needing to be due to the one diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIce pack application and analgesia\u003C/strong\u003E may provide temporary symptomatic relief for bruising from trauma, but do not address the underlying emergency. The pain from the football strike would be painful but demonstrate a pattern of relief over time rather than persisting high pain, irrespective of his pain tolerance. These measures alone are insufficient and potentially harmful if they delay definitive treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinalysis and urine culture\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered in cases of suspected urinary tract infection or epididymitis, but they are not the priority in a case of suspected testicular torsion where time is critical.  This may be done due to the presence of white discharge but secondary to surgical exploration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe classic presentation of testicular torsion includes sudden-onset scrotal pain, which is often accompanied by nausea and vomiting. On examination, the affected testis may be high-riding and the cremasteric reflex is typically absent. This case has all these features, strongly supporting the diagnosis of testicular torsion. Given the time-sensitive nature of this condition, with the best outcomes achieved if detorsion occurs within six hours of symptom onset, immediate surgical exploration is crucial to confirm the diagnosis and salvage the testis if possible. While the patient\u0027s sexual history is relevant and should be addressed, it should not delay the management of the more urgent condition of testicular torsion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Testicular torsion is a surgical emergency requiring immediate exploration, ideally within six hours of symptom onset.","Clinical diagnosis of testicular torsion is often sufficient, and imaging should not delay surgical intervention.","The classic presentation of testicular torsion includes sudden-onset scrotal pain, swelling, and nausea/vomiting."],"references":["Steinhardt GF, Hensle TW. Causes of scrotal pain in children and adolescents. UpToDate. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/causes-of-scrotal-pain-in-children-and-adolescents?search=testicular%20torsion\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=2%7E39\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=2"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92682"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13991"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92682"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-31T00:18:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-27T13:57:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6625"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110418"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/